SATIRE 6. There probably never was a nation in which family pride was stronger than it was among the Romans, And this pride had its natural accompaniment of mean servility and vulgar striving for social and political advancement. Horace, of low, birth but recom- mended by his talents to the favor of the great, seems to have been a mark for all sorts of attacks from envious rivals and ignoble souls. But his whole life and writings show a remarkable freedom from all vulgar social ambitions, and a truly refined sels-respect and inde- pendence. This Satire is an answer to the attacks of his enemies, and a statement of his creed in regard to social position.
